Subject:  )  Where can I get an "X terminal" server for my low-end Sun /?

	Seth Robertson (seth@ctr.columbia.edu) has written Xkernel; the current
version [. as of /, . expected RSN] is on sol.ctr.columbia.edu 
[...] in /pub/Xkernel.gamma. It turns a Sun / into a pseudo- X 
terminal; most of the overhead of the operating system is side-stepped, so it 
is fairly fast and needs little disk space.
	A similar approach is to run the regular X server by making /etc/init
a shell script which does the minimal setup and then invokes Xsun, like this
example script from mouse@larry.mcrcim.mcgill.EDU:

#! /bin/sh
exec >/dev/console >&
/etc/fsck -p /dev/nd
case $? in
 	)	;;
 	)	/etc/reboot -q -n
 		;;
 	)	echo ND fsck failed - get help
 		/etc/halt
 		;;
 	)	echo Interrupted
 		/etc/reboot
 		;;
 	*)	echo Unknown error in reboot fsck - get help
 		/etc/halt
 		;;
esac
/bin/dd if=/tmp-fs of=/dev/nd bs= count= >/dev/null >&
/etc/mount /dev/nd /tmp
/etc/ifconfig le netmask ... broadcast ...
/etc/mount -o ro apollo:/u/x/lib /local/lib/X
/etc/route add default ...  >/dev/null
set `/etc/ifconfig le`
exec /Xsun -once -multidisp -mux -query \
	`(sh -vn </local/lib/X/xdm-servers/$ >&)`

